<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06206090 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06206090 </ACCESS><LEADPARA>  The income gap between rich and poor widened in the 1980s, with averageincomes increasing 122 percent after taxes for the top 1 percent of householdsbut falling 10 percent for the bottom fifth, according to a study releasedTuesday.;    For the top 1 percent income measured in today's dollars rosefrom an average of $203,000 per household in 1977 to $451,000 in 1988,according to the Center on Budget and Policy Priorities, a liberal think tank.The study found that for the poorest one-fifth of households, average cashincome after taxes dropped 10 percent. For the second-poorest fifth, itdropped 3 percent. For the middle fifth it rose 4 percent, for the nexthighest fifth, 9 percent, and for the richest fifth, 34 percent.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Business  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  RICH-POOR GAP GROWS IN '80S, STUDY FINDS  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  Financial Digest  </MEMO><BYLINE>  Mercury News Staff and Wire Reports  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910724  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Wednesday  </DAY><MONTH>  July  </MONTH><PG.COL>  2F  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  129  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Wednesday July 24, 199100206090,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>